                    <msContents>
                        <summary> A volume of copperplate engravings produced to accompany the work Seisetsu ihan teikō shakugi, with illustrations by Aōdō Denzen (1748-1822) and text by Udagawa Genshin (1769-1834), published in 1808. The plates for this book were printed sheet by sheet and pasted onto thick card on which the commentary had already been printed using woodblocks. </summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="ja" source="IANA">Japanese</textLang>

                        <msItem n="1" xml:id="Japanese_70">

                            <author key="person_7323189" source="VIAF">
                                <persName type="original" xml:lang="ja">宇田川玄真</persName>
                                <persName type="standard" xml:lang="ja-Latn">Udagawa Genshin</persName>
                                <note><p>Udagawa Genshin (1769-1834) was unusual among scholars of
                                        ‘Dutch studies’ in Japan in having a knowledge of French.
                                        Udagawa as a young man studied under the pioneers of anatomy
                                        in Japan, Sugita Genpaku and Ōtsuki Gentaku, and the ‘Gen’
                                        in his pen-name reflects this intellectual genealogy. After
                                        being adopted into the Udagawa family of doctors in Tsuyama,
                                        in addition to practicing medicine he was employed by the
                                        Bakufu as a translator of Dutch astronomical texts and in
                                        his school, Fūundō, he taught not only medicine but also
                                        chemistry and other scientific subjects.</p></note>
                            </author>

                            <respStmt key="person_72556522" source="VIAF">
                                <persName type="original" xml:lang="ja">亜欧堂田善</persName>
                                <persName type="standard" xml:lang="ja-Latn">Aōdō Denzen</persName>
                                <resp>Illustrator</resp>
                                <note>Aōdō Denzen was a pioneer of copperplate printing in Japan,
                                    and spent four years studying the technique in Nagasaki</note>
                            </respStmt>

                                <title type="original" xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">解剖銅図</title>
                                <title type="standard" xml:lang="ja-Latn" source="IANA">Kaibō dōzu</title>
                                <title type="standard" xml:lang="en" source="IANA">Copperplate anatomical illustrations</title>                           

